==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested around 1400.
* {{suffix|en|account|able}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/əˈkaʊntəbl̩/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-accountable.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Obliged, when called upon, to answer (for one’s deeds); [[answerable]].
#: {{ux|en|Every man is '''accountable''' to God for his conduct.}}
#: {{ux|en|You will be held '''accountable''' for your misdemeanors.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2020 April 22|author=Philip Haigh|title=Labour's blueprint for the future of Britain's railways|journal=Rail|page=28|text="Because the railway is economically and socially vital, it receives large amounts of public money and must therefore ultimately be '''accountable''' to government. [...]}}
# Obliged to keep accurate [[records]] (of [[property]] or [[funds]]).
# [[liable|Liable]] to be called on to render an account.
# {{lb|en|rare}} Capable of being [[accounted]] for; [[explicable]]; [[explainable]].
#* {{quote-book|en|passage=True religion . . . intelligible, rational, and '''accountable''', -- not a burden but a privilege.|author={{w|Benjamin Whichcote}}|title=Moral and Religious Aphorisms|year=1703}}

